## Overview

Permissions are a **fixed, server-defined registry** — they are created and
maintained in the product, not by Terraform. This data source is read-only and
**cannot create permissions**; it lists every permission the instance defines,
optionally filtered by module and/or a fuzzy search term. It is the authoritative
on-product enumeration of valid permission names for the
[`mistershell_role`](../resources/role.md) `permissions` attribute.

## Filter arguments

Both are optional; omit both to return the entire registry.

| argument | behavior |
|---|---|
| `module` | Server-side filter: return only permissions belonging to this module. |
| `search` | Server-side fuzzy search across permission fields. |

## Returned values

| attribute | description |
|---|---|
| `id` | Synthetic constant (`permissions`); this is a list data source with no primary key. |
| `modules` | Set of all unique module names in the registry. |
| `permissions` | List of matching permissions. Each element is an object with the fields below. |

Each element of `permissions` has:

| field | description |
|---|---|
| `name` | Permission name, e.g. `app.tags.read` or `*.*.*`. |
| `description` | Human-readable description of what the permission grants. |
| `module` | The module the permission belongs to. |
| `action` | The action the permission grants (`read`, `write`, `delete`, `execute`, or `all`). |

## Modules

The registry currently defines 27 modules: `ai`, `audit`, `auth_providers`,
`automation`, `backup`, `changelog`, `commands`, `credentials`, `licenses`,
`logs`, `metrics`, `motd`, `notes`, `permissions`, `policy`, `reports`,
`resources`, `roles`, `session`, `settings`, `snaps`, `snapshots`, `system`,
`tags`, `tasks`, `users`, `workers`. Use any of these as the `module` filter.
The live set is also returned in the `modules` attribute.

## Example output usage

Feed the data source straight into a role to keep the permission list in sync
with the server:

```hcl
# All permissions for the "tags" module.
data "mistershell_permissions" "tags" {
  module = "tags"
}

resource "mistershell_role" "tag_admin" {
  name        = "tag-admin"
  permissions = [for p in data.mistershell_permissions.tags.permissions : p.name]
}

# Every permission name defined on the instance.
data "mistershell_permissions" "all" {}

output "permission_names" {
  value = [for p in data.mistershell_permissions.all.permissions : p.name]
}
```
